DB schema — new table, purely additive

Yes, one new table — no modification to any existing table. scores, fundamentals, etc. stay untouched. This is the safe, standard pattern (a new Alembic migration that only does CREATE TABLE).

Two design facts that fall out of how the codebase already works:

- It's a global table, not tenant-scoped — no tenant_id, no RLS. A price target for RELIANCE is identical for every user (it's research output, like scores). Contrast with alert_rules/portfolios, which are tenant-scoped with RLS. So it mirrors scores, not alerts.
- Same PIT + versioning + partitioning discipline as scores — append-only (never mutate a past row; a revision is a new row), model_version fingerprint, partitioned by date.

Concretely, modelled directly on your scores table (migration 0006):

CREATE TABLE price_targets (
    id              bigint GENERATED ALWAYS AS IDENTITY,
    stock_id        uuid NOT NULL REFERENCES stocks(id),
    date            date NOT NULL,              -- as-of date (PIT)
    horizon_months  smallint NOT NULL,          -- 6 / 12 — a stock can have several
    target_price    numeric(14, 4) NOT NULL,    -- money as Decimal, never float
    expected_return numeric(7, 4),              -- (target - current)/current
    rating          text NOT NULL,              -- buy | hold | sell
    confidence_lo   numeric(14, 4),             -- target RANGE, not false precision
    confidence_hi   numeric(14, 4),
    method          text NOT NULL,              -- relative | dcf | ml | blend
    rationale       jsonb,                       -- the drivers, for the disclosure trail
    model_version   text NOT NULL,              -- methodology fingerprint (like scores)
    created_at      timestamptz NOT NULL DEFAULT now(),
    PRIMARY KEY (id, date),
    UNIQUE (stock_id, date, horizon_months, method)
) PARTITION BY RANGE (date);

CREATE INDEX ix_price_targets_stock_date ON price_targets (stock_id, date DESC);

Notes on the choices:
- horizon_months in the key — because 6m and 12m targets coexist on the same date.
- method in the key — lets you persist a valuation target and an ML target side-by-side for comparison; if you only ever want one canonical row, drop method from the UNIQUE.
- rationale jsonb — the factor/driver breakdown. This isn't just nice-to-have: for SEBI RA you must be able to show why a rating was issued, so the rationale trail is a compliance artifact, not decoration.
- confidence_lo/hi — ship a range, never a bare point estimate.
- Reuse the existing _bootstrap_partitions("price_targets") helper from 0006 — same monthly-range partition machinery.

Serving would be a new price_targets read repo + an API route, exactly parallel to how scores is read today — but that's application code, not schema.